# Go Testing Standards

## The testing philosophy
Tests are first-class production code. They have the same quality bar as implementation code. A flaky test is a broken test. A slow test that can be parallelised is a broken test.

## Naming — every test must be instantly readable

```go
// WRONG — says nothing about the scenario or expected outcome
func TestGet(t *testing.T) {}
func TestAgentStore(t *testing.T) {}
func Test1(t *testing.T) {}

// RIGHT — TestUnit_Scenario or TestUnit_Scenario_ExpectedOutcome
func TestAgentStore_GetByIDAndOrg_ReturnsNilOnCrossOrgLookup(t *testing.T) {}
func TestRedisSlider_Check_FailsOpenWhenRedisDown(t *testing.T) {}
func TestRateLimitMiddleware_Returns429WithRetryAfterHeader(t *testing.T) {}
```

## Table-driven tests for multiple scenarios of the same function

```go
// WRONG — copy-pasted tests
func TestCheck_UnderLimit(t *testing.T) { ... }
func TestCheck_OverLimit(t *testing.T) { ... }
func TestCheck_AtLimit(t *testing.T) { ... }

// RIGHT — one table, runs in parallel, easy to add cases
func TestRedisSlider_Check(t *testing.T) {
    t.Parallel()

    tests := []struct {
        name        string
        requests    int
        limit       int64
        wantAllowed bool
        wantRemain  int64
    }{
        {name: "under limit", requests: 10, limit: 60, wantAllowed: true, wantRemain: 50},
        {name: "at limit",    requests: 60, limit: 60, wantAllowed: true, wantRemain: 0},
        {name: "over limit",  requests: 61, limit: 60, wantAllowed: false, wantRemain: 0},
    }

    for _, tc := range tests {
        tc := tc // capture range variable (Go < 1.22)
        t.Run(tc.name, func(t *testing.T) {
            t.Parallel()
            // arrange
            mr := miniredis.RunT(t)
            slider := NewRedisSlider(redis.NewClient(&redis.Options{Addr: mr.Addr()}), tc.limit)
            // act
            var result ratelimit.Result
            for i := 0; i < tc.requests; i++ {
                result, _ = slider.Check(t.Context(), testOrgID)
            }
            // assert
            if result.Allowed != tc.wantAllowed {
                t.Errorf("Allowed = %v, want %v", result.Allowed, tc.wantAllowed)
            }
        })
    }
}
```

## t.Parallel() — always on parallelisable tests

Call `t.Parallel()` as the first line of every `Test*` function that does not modify shared state. Integration tests that hit a shared DB are exempt if they use separate orgs (preferred) or use transactions.

## No time.Sleep in tests

```go
// WRONG — flaky; different machines have different timing
time.Sleep(100 * time.Millisecond)
assert(result)

// RIGHT — poll with eventual consistency or use channels/sync primitives
require.Eventually(t, func() bool {
    return getValue() == expected
}, 5*time.Second, 10*time.Millisecond)

// RIGHT — use synchronisation primitives
done := make(chan struct{})
go func() { doWork(); close(done) }()
select {
case <-done:
case <-time.After(5 * time.Second):
    t.Fatal("timed out waiting for work")
}
```

## Arrange-Act-Assert structure — always

Every test function follows AAA. Separate the three phases with a blank line. Never mix assertion and setup.

```go
func TestTokenService_Revoke_MarksTokenAsRevoked(t *testing.T) {
    t.Parallel()

    // Arrange
    svc, store := buildTestService(t)
    token := store.InsertTestToken(t, testOrgID)

    // Act
    err := svc.Revoke(t.Context(), token.ID)

    // Assert
    if err != nil {
        t.Fatalf("unexpected error: %v", err)
    }
    got, _ := store.GetByID(t.Context(), token.ID)
    if !got.IsRevoked {
        t.Error("expected token to be revoked")
    }
}
```

## Test helpers — use t.Helper() religiously

```go
// WRONG — failure points to helper line, not test line
func createOrg(pool *pgxpool.Pool) uuid.UUID {
    // ...
}

// RIGHT — t.Helper() makes error point to the CALLER
func createTestOrg(t *testing.T, pool *pgxpool.Pool) uuid.UUID {
    t.Helper()
    // ...
}
```

## Integration vs unit — tag every integration test

```go
//go:build integration
// +build integration

package store_test

// Integration tests run with: go test -tags=integration ./...
// They require real Postgres/Redis (from compose-test stack).
// Unit tests must run without any external infrastructure.
```

## No assertions in goroutines — use t.Fatal only in main goroutine

```go
// WRONG — t.Fatal in goroutine causes panic, not test failure
go func() {
    result := compute()
    if result != expected {
        t.Fatalf("wrong result") // PANIC: called from non-test goroutine
    }
}()

// RIGHT — communicate result back to main goroutine
resultCh := make(chan int, 1)
go func() { resultCh <- compute() }()
result := <-resultCh
if result != expected {
    t.Errorf("compute() = %d, want %d", result, expected)
}
```

## Coverage requirements

- **Merged Go profile (unit + integration): ≥ 94%** — enforced by `infra/scripts/coverage-gate.sh` in CI
- Packages in `packages/*`: ≥ 90% statement coverage
- `services/*/internal/middleware/*`: ≥ 85% statement coverage
- `services/*/internal/store/*`: ≥ 80% statement coverage
- `services/*/internal/grpc/*`: ≥ 80% statement coverage
- CI fails below these thresholds.

## Forbidden in tests

- No `assert.True(t, err == nil)` — use `require.NoError` or `if err != nil { t.Fatal }`
- No global test state (package-level `var` modified by tests)
- No production database — always use testcontainers or miniredis
- No hardcoded ports — let the OS assign ephemeral ports
- No `fmt.Println` for test debugging — use `t.Log`
